conclusion: Consider the forces acting on the objects to determine what will happen.
Objects A and B are moving through the air and will experience air resistance.
Objects C, D, E, F are stationary and will not experience air resistance.
Air resistance acts against the motion of objects and opposes the force of gravity.
Objects A and B will experience the force of gravity.
Net force on objects A and B is calculated as Force of gravity minus Force of air resistance.
Force of gravity is calculated as F_g = mg, where m is the mass and g is the acceleration due to gravity.
Force of air resistance is calculated as F_a = 1/2 ρ v^2 A, where ρ is the air density, v is the velocity, and A is the area.
For objects A and B, net force is zero minus air resistance force, as mass is considered zero.
Direction of net force is opposite to the motion of objects A and B since net force is zero.
Objects A and B will slow down due to air resistance and accelerate downward due to gravity.
Objects A and B will eventually come to a stop due to air resistance and accelerate downward due to gravity.
Final answer: Objects A and B will come to a stop due to air resistance and come into contact with objects C, D, E, F due to gravity.
